 BC-APTV Outlook,1050 

      APTV 1800 GMT OUTLOOK TUESDAY JUNE 2, 1998   For Planner / Newsdesk use - stories expected to move in the next 12 hours. All times are GMT.  ---- EXPECTED: ---- US: EINSTEIN - Nine recently discovered letters belonging to Albert Einstein suggest he had a romance during and after World War II with a woman thought to be a Soviet spy.  The letters, complete with pet names and warm recollections of the couple's time together, reveal Einstein's strong feelings for Margarita Konenkova.  APTV has the story.  (Expected first run 1830 North America Late) ---- US: CHINA - APTV has an interview with Chinese dissident Wei Jingsheng ahead of the June 4th anniversary of the Tiananmen Square massacre in 1989.  (Expected first run F-l-a-s-h after 2100 GMT) ---- AFGHAN: AID -  APTV has coverage of a news conference in Faisabad by officials assisting with the aid effort following an earthquake which killed thousands.  Aid workers say the zone of devastation is 60 percent larger than originally thought. (F-l-a-s-h at 1800 gmt) ---- US: SHUTTLE L-I-V-E - APTV will have live coverage of the lift-off of the space shuttle Discovery from Cape Canaveral in Florida, on the last mission to the Russian Mir space station expected. (Expected 2210 GMT) ---- US: VOTING - APTV will have early voting scenes in California where people are deciding on a controversial ballot measure which could change the way the state runs its bilingual education programs. (Expected first run 1930 North America Update) The story will be updated overnight with results of the vote. ---- MEXICO: AIRLINES - The Mexican government has halted a massive strike by airline staff by taking over operations at the country's main airport, Aeromexico.  The intervention forced 1,000 flight attendants back to work after just two hours on strike. The strikers are hoping that discussions between the government and their Union will pay off.  (Expected first run 1900 Latin America) ---- MEXICO: FIRES - Ten Mexican fire-fighters have been killed in a helicopter crash in the mountainous region where fires are spreading, fanned by the El Nino weather phenomenon and droughts. Smoke from the blazes has blanketed Mexico and the southern states of the US, prompting health alerts throughout the region.  APTV reports.  (Expected first run 1900 Latin America) ---- VENEZUELA: OAS - APTV reports from Caracas, where delegates from the Organisation of American States have been challenged over US policy towards Cuba.  Package will include a news conference by US Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.  (Expected first run 2130 Latin America Update) ---- COLOMBIA: SAMPER -  APTV has an interview with Colombian President Ernesto Samper.  Samper says he has a dossier of threats against his life - from drug traffickers, leftist rebels, paramilitary groups and political foes - and is considering leaving the country. (Expected first run 2130 Latin America Update) ---- RUNNING: ---- AFGHAN: WRAP - Helicopters shipped in building supplies and evacuated more injured from northern Afghanistan on Tuesday in the aftermath of the earthquake.  The death toll has been climbing steadily and as many as 5,000 people are believed to have died in the 6.9 magnitude quake.  APTV reports from Faisabad and Shegani-Chavgani. Includes aftermath pictures and arrival of aid workers. (First ran 1500 Europe Late) ---- FRANCE: STRIKE - Pilots for Air France, the official carrier for next week's World Cup, have stayed off the job for a second day. APTV has coverage of the strike causing chaos for more than 100-thousand travellers. (First ran 1300 F-L-A-S-H) ---- US: SPACE - APTV has a feature on the future of US-Russian cooperation in space.  Pictures include, Russian space station Mir, space shuttle missions, international space station and interviews with NASA officials and astronauts. (First Ran 1440 APTV Eurovision) ---- US: NAZI GOLD - A new US government reports says neutral nations kept Nazi Germany's war machine running with hundreds of millions of dollars of trade in key materials.  APTV's package includes the news conference by Stuart Eizenstadt, Undersecretary of State for Economics who is the author of the report.  (First ran 1500 Europe Late) ---- GENEVA: DISARMAMENT - APTV has coverage of the UN Conference on Disarmament holding an emergency meeting on Tuesday to discuss the fall out from the news that both India and Pakistan have tested nuclear weapons in the last month.  In a joint statement, 46 countries said the tests threatened the goal of nuclear disarmament. (First ran 1130 Europe Update) ---- SWITZERLAND: LABOUR - APTV has pictures of a protest march by hundreds of children ending a five month global march aimed at stamping out child labour.  Package also includes protests inside the International Labour Organisation and sound from the Director General of the ILO. (First run 1130 gmt Europe Update) ---- RUSSIA: TAX 2 - Amid a worsening economic crisis, Russian President Boris Yeltsin  has blasted the country's financial chiefs over their inability to collect taxes.  APTV has pictures of Yeltsin meeting with financial chiefs, the Union of Russian Taxpayers founding congress and comments from Russia's new tax tsar, Boris Fyodorov. (First ran 1130 Europe Update) ---- GREENPEACE: GLACIERS -  As a UN conference dedicated to finding an agreement on global cuts to greenhouse gases reopens in Bonn, environmentalists are warning that a rapid increase in regional temperatures has already caused North American glaciers to retreat and thin.  APTV has pictures from Prince William Sound and Majuro in the South Pacific where sea levels are rising on the low lying islands.  (First ran 1130 Europe Update) ---- ---- Editor of the Day: - 44 171 427 4163 Master Control Room - 44 171 427 4131 ---- APTV       (PROFILE (REG:ASIA;) (REG:ENGL;) (REG:EURO;) (REG:BRIT;) (REG:SCAN;) (REG:MEST;) (REG:AFRI;) (REG:INDI;) (LANG:ENGLISH;)) ) 

